was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26480","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26480","title":"Create global objects","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26480","severity":"medium","group_title":"Create global objects","rule_id_src":"SV-35935r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35935","rule_version":"WINUR-000013","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Create global objects user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create global objects\" to only include the following accounts or groups:\n\nAdministrators\nService\nLocal Service\nNetwork Service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups other than the following are granted the \"Create global objects\" right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators\nService\nLocal Service\nNetwork Service","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create global objects\" user right can create objects that are available to all sessions, which could affect processes in other users' sessions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"3611","uuid":"0de425d7-cece-4d10-87a5-fefed4d39341","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 1172748333711759C0599895DE1241D39654BA18\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Create global objects user right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26481","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26481","title":"Create permanent shared objects","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26481","severity":"medium","group_title":"Create permanent shared objects","rule_id_src":"SV-35936r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35936","rule_version":"WINUR-000014","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Create permanent shared objects user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create permanent shared objects\" to be defined but containing no entries (blank).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups are granted the \"Create permanent shared objects\" right, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create permanent shared objects\" user right could expose sensitive data by creating shared objects.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"9345","uuid":"457dbd06-7542-4aff-aa6d-9f5517544d9e","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 674C96E0068C64F7942EEF0BEA9394E09845A862\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Create permanent shared objects user right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26482","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26482","title":"Create symbolic links","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26482","severity":"medium","group_title":"Create symbolic links","rule_id_src":"SV-35937r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35937","rule_version":"WINUR-000015","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Create symbolic links user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Create symbolic links\" to only include the following accounts or groups:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups other than the following are granted the \"Create symbolic links\" right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Create symbolic links\" user right can create pointers to other objects, which could potentially expose the system to attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"8228","uuid":"c2ba3d63-de6e-48e4-99cf-33372eacf51d","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 953751E5BCA48930090447B4486AAEE372DC27E6\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Create symbolic links user right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26483","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26483","title":"Deny log on as a batch job","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26483","severity":"medium","group_title":"Deny log on as a batch job","rule_id_src":"SV-35938r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35938","rule_version":"WINUR-000018","rule_title":"The Deny log on as a batch job user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Local Policies -> User Rights Assignment -> \"Deny log on as a batch job\" to include the following.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests Group","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.  Expand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view. \nNavigate to Local Policies -> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following accounts or groups are not defined for the \"Deny log on as a batch job\" right, this is a finding.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests Group","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on as a batch job\" right defines accounts that are prevented from logging on to the system as a batch job, such as Task Scheduler.  \n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nThe Guests group must be assigned to prevent unauthenticated access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"9402","uuid":"f768fbf3-1eba-4a5e-b52e-684462c55e26","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: B9A7E0C6CC556616143B87491E1C478FEF5BAE3C\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'The Deny log on as a batch job user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.' matches the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26484","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26484","title":"Deny log on as service","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26484","severity":"medium","group_title":"Deny log on as service","rule_id_src":"SV-35939r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35939","rule_version":"WINUR-000019","rule_title":"The Deny log on as a service user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems.  No other groups or accounts must be assigned this right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Local Policies -> User Rights Assignment -> \"Deny log on as a service\" to include the following for domain joined systems.\n\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nConfigure the \"Deny log on as a service\" for non-domain systems to include no entries (blank).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in. Expand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view. \nNavigate to Local Policies -> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following accounts or groups are not defined for the \"Deny log on as a service\" right on domain joined systems, this is a finding:\n\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nIf any accounts or groups are defined for the \"Deny log on as a service\" right on non-domain joined systems, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on as a service\" right defines accounts that are denied log on as a service.  \n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nIncorrect configurations could prevent services from starting and result in a DoS.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"7741","uuid":"e582c153-6b46-44ed-b0cb-c1bad6dbd973","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: A360E03705D7A79415A7D274CF9B198A257F098D\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Deny log on as a service user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems.  No other groups or accounts must be assigned this right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26485","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26485","title":"Deny log on locally","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26485","severity":"medium","group_title":"Deny log on locally","rule_id_src":"SV-35940r3_rule","rule_id":"SV-35940","rule_version":"WINUR-000020","rule_title":"The Deny log on locally user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration -> Windows Settings -> Security Settings -> Local Policies -> User Rights Assignment -> \"Deny log on locally\" to include the following.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nWorkstations dedicated to the management of Active Directory (see V-36436 in the Active Directory Domain STIG) are exempt from this.\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests Group","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in. Expand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view. \nNavigate to Local Policies -> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following accounts or groups are not defined for the \"Deny log on locally\" right, this is a finding.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins Group\nDomain Admins Group\n\nWorkstations dedicated to the management of Active Directory (see V-36436 in the Active Directory Domain STIG) are exempt from this.\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests Group","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on locally\" right defines accounts that are prevented from logging on interactively.  \n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nThe Guests group must be assigned this right to prevent unauthenticated access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"2612","uuid":"340fdd63-7657-4cd1-aa23-b17d04a3f86a","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C7CEDC7ADBBC548A4859CAF5A228C5BCA1913AFC\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'The Deny log on locally user right on workstations must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26486","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26486","title":"Deny log on through Remote Desktop \\ Terminal Services","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26486","severity":"medium","group_title":"Deny log on through Remote Desktop \\ Terminal Services","rule_id_src":"SV-35941r5_rule","rule_id":"SV-35941","rule_version":"WINUR-000021","rule_title":"The Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services user right on workstations must prevent all access if RDS is not used by the organization.  If RDS is used, it must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts and all local accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services\" to include the following.\n\nIf Remote Desktop Services is not used by the organization, assign the Everyone group this right to prevent all access.\n\nIf RDS is used by the organization, assign the following groups.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins group\nDomain Admins group\nLocal account (see Note below)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests group\n\nSystems dedicated to the management of Active Directory (AD admin platforms, see V-36436 in the Active Directory Domain STIG) are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups.\n\nNote: Microsoft Security Advisory Patch 2871997 adds new built-in security groups, including \"Local account\", to Windows 7 for assigning permissions and rights to all local accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in. Expand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view. \nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf the following accounts or groups are not defined for the \"Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services\" right, this is a finding.\n\nIf Remote Desktop Services is not used by the organization, the Everyone group can replace all of the groups listed below.\n\nDomain Systems Only:\nEnterprise Admins group\nDomain Admins group\nLocal account (see Note below)\n\nAll Systems:\nGuests group\n\nSystems dedicated to the management of Active Directory (AD admin platforms, see V-36436 in the Active Directory Domain STIG) are exempt from denying the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups.\n\nNote: Microsoft Security Advisory Patch 2871997 adds new built-in security groups, including \"Local account\", to Windows 7 for assigning permissions and rights to all local accounts.","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services\" right defines the accounts that are prevented from logging on using Remote Desktop Services.\n\nIf Remote Desktop Services is not used by the organization, the Everyone group must be assigned this right to prevent all access.\n\nIn an Active Directory Domain, denying logons to the Enterprise Admins and Domain Admins groups on lower trust systems helps mitigate the risk of privilege escalation from credential theft attacks which could lead to the compromise of an entire domain.\n\nLocal accounts on domain-joined systems must also be assigned this right to decrease the risk of lateral movement resulting from credential theft attacks.\n\nThe Guests group must be assigned this right to prevent unauthenticated access.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"5323","uuid":"60470690-e768-4de5-947b-5fe7b9899412","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Not applicable - capability not installed/enabled on this asset.","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) marked this Not_Applicable on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 63732F295BAAB8DE03CFDF17E16190B03E7209B6\r\n~~~~~\r\nThe feature/role addressed by 'The Deny log on through Remote Desktop Services user right on workstations must prevent all access if RDS is not used by the organization.  If RDS is used, it must be configured to prevent access from highly privileged domain accounts and all local accounts on domain systems and unauthenticated access on all systems.' is not present or not in use on this the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26487","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26487","title":"Enable accounts to be trusted for delegation","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26487","severity":"medium","group_title":"Enable accounts to be trusted for delegation","rule_id_src":"SV-35942r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35942","rule_version":"WINUR-000022","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation\" to be defined but containing no entries (blank).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups are granted the \"Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation\" right, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation\" user right allows the \"Trusted for Delegation\" setting to be changed.  This could potentially allow unauthorized users to impersonate other users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"4046","uuid":"11d3c5f5-c954-4781-bac2-55f39d227fa9","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: C45415E2EA73F9A4F92862C6ACE34FB440C72D22\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Enable computer and user accounts to be trusted for delegation user right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26488","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26488","title":"Force shutdown from a remote system","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26488","severity":"medium","group_title":"Force shutdown from a remote system","rule_id_src":"SV-35943r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35943","rule_version":"WINUR-000023","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Force shutdown from a remote system user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Force shutdown from a remote system\" to only include the following accounts or groups:\n\nAdministrators","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups other than the following are granted the \"Force shutdown from a remote system\" right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nAccounts with the \"Force shutdown from a remote system\" user right can remotely shut down a system which could result in a DoS.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"1820","uuid":"3caab027-4b0b-49a3-828c-8bea508d914d","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"notafinding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be NotAFinding on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: 114EE8203A52AE98EA2D312579710617F0E00709\r\n~~~~~\r\nConfiguration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Force shutdown from a remote system user right.' matches the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26489","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26489","title":"Generate security audits","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26489","severity":"medium","group_title":"Generate security audits","rule_id_src":"SV-35944r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35944","rule_version":"WINUR-000024","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Generate security audits user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Generate security audits\" to only include the following accounts or groups:\n\nLocal Service\nNetwork Service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups other than the following are granted the \"Generate security audits\" right, this is a finding:\n\nLocal Service\nNetwork Service","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Generate security audits\" user right specifies users and processes that can generate Security Log audit records, which must only be the system service accounts defined.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"8761","uuid":"c96bb5ca-2f3a-46eb-89e3-39bfa6618c32","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: CAFDE39E6F7A9FFD3801DABB51158F0EA3E4FDC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Generate security audits user right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26490","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26490","title":"Impersonate a client after authentication","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-26490","severity":"medium","group_title":"Impersonate a client after authentication","rule_id_src":"SV-35945r2_rule","rule_id":"SV-35945","rule_version":"WINUR-000025","rule_title":"Unauthorized accounts must not have the Impersonate a client after authentication user right.","fix_text":"Configure the policy value for Computer Configuration >> Windows Settings >> Security Settings >> Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment >> \"Impersonate a client after authentication\" to only include the following accounts or groups:\n\nAdministrators\nService\nLocal Service\nNetwork Service","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Analyze the system using the Security Configuration and Analysis snap-in.\nExpand the Security Configuration and Analysis tree view.\nNavigate to Local Policies >> User Rights Assignment.\n\nIf any accounts or groups other than the following are granted the \"Impersonate a client after authentication\" right, this is a finding:\n\nAdministrators\nService\nLocal Service\nNetwork Service","check_content_ref":{"href":"DPMS_XCCDF_Benchmark_Windows_7_STIG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inappropriate granting of user rights can provide system, administrative, and other high-level capabilities.\n\nThe \"Impersonate a client after authentication\" user right allows a program to impersonate another user or account to run on their behalf.  An attacker could potentially use this to elevate privileges.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2686","uuid":"af8c291a-dc5b-421e-acd1-aa4fec51eef0","stig_uuid":"c72758fa-0fec-48d0-b90f-cf02bbeace21","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2604.2 (Scan-Windows7_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 07/23/2026\r\nResultHash: ABC6048101C6FBB9468FE888930A12C4466AFBC8\r\n~~~~~\r\nRequired configuration for 'Unauthorized accounts must not have the Impersonate a client after authentication user right.' was not present or did not match the expected value on the Windows 7 workstation."},{"group_id_src":"V-26492","group_tree":[{"id":"V-26492","title":"Increase scheduling priority","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"gro